			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Using Selenium for our in-browser tests is buying us very little.

Selenium knows how to launch Firefox with a new profile.  But its browser-launching ability has had problems that are proving difficult to fix (issue 1150).  We could implement this ourselves.

Selenium has some ability to evaluate Javascript in the context of the page, which we use to find out a test's status (see getStatus() and getMessage()), but we could easily replace this with an XHR to the HTTP server (as proposed in issue 735).  We are supplying the HTTP server in our selenium_tester.py anyway.

selenium_tester.py is complicated and does a lot of polling.  It launches the Selenium server process and scrapes its output.  It produces a lot of incomprehensible logging output.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-07-29T00:12:47.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-11-10T14:26:52.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:state>closed</ns2:state><ns0:title>Rid ourselves of Selenium for browser tests</ns0:title><ns2:label>Type-Enhancement</ns2:label><ns2:label>Pri-3</ns2:label><ns2:label>OS-Linux</ns2:label><ns2:label>OS-Mac</ns2:label><ns2:label>Test</ns2:label><ns2:label>Component-Infrastructure</ns2:label><ns2:label>Mstone-X</ns2:label><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/1151/comments/full" rel="replies" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=1151" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/1151" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns2:stars>1</ns2:stars><ns2:closedDate>2011-07-07T23:56:41.000Z</ns2:closedDate><ns2:id>1151</ns2:id></ns0:entry>